on. So we wanted to ask, what would happen if we targeted this molecule?

1216
01:09:50.084 --> 01:09:54.065
So we used an experimental design that we thought was going to be very difficult.

1217
01:09:54.324 --> 01:09:57.864
We took these mice that have been treated long-term with PD-1 blockade, and we

1218
01:09:57.904 --> 01:10:00.764
simply added on a blocking antibody to CD22.

1219
01:10:01.324 --> 01:10:03.964
And for those of you that have been doing this a long time, this is the place where

1220
01:10:04.024 --> 01:10:07.744
all drugs fail. When patients progress on PD-1 and we add on another checkpoint,

1221
01:10:07.784 --> 01:10:10.784
this is extremely difficult to get responses there.

1222
01:10:11.284 --> 01:10:14.864
In fact, LAG-3 is a good example where the first trial with LAG-3 in

1223
01:10:14.944 --> 01:10:18.714
humans was to take PD-1 progressers in melanoma and add on LAG-3.

1224
01:10:19.184 --> 01:10:22.834
Clinical response rates there were around 11% to 13% when

1225
01:10:23.044 --> 01:10:25.484
BMS finally put that therapy up front.

1226
01:10:25.864 --> 01:10:29.644
So primary treatment with PD-1 and LAG-3, you saw about a 39% or 40% clinical

1227
01:10:29.704 --> 01:10:32.753
response rate. So this is a very high bar to see if we could get a response in this

1228
01:10:32.784 --> 01:10:36.764
setting. But indeed, when we did this, we saw that there was a major boost

1229
01:10:36.884 --> 01:10:39.764
in reinvigorating those exhausted T cells. So this is pre-therapy.

1230
01:10:39.864 --> 01:10:42.884
The groups are pretty similar. In fact, the group that's going to get

1231
01:10:43.324 --> 01:10:47.284
anti-CD22 may be a tad lower, but actually they do

1232
01:10:47.304 --> 01:10:51.224
much better afterwards. And in fact, that results in control

1233
01:10:51.324 --> 01:10:55.144
of systemic viral replication by adding on a blocking antibody to

1234
01:10:55.164 --> 01:10:56.044
CD22 late.

1235
01:10:57.184 --> 01:11:01.124
So we did a lot of things here. We looked early in primary treatment

1236
01:11:01.184 --> 01:11:04.244
early. I'm not going to show you that data in the interest of time.

1237
01:11:04.284 --> 01:11:08.164
We also did experiments in B cell depleted mice that said that at least part of

1238
01:11:08.224 --> 01:11:11.724
this response, probably most of this effect, is not dependent on B cells.

1239
01:11:12.164 --> 01:11:15.584
I can't exclude a role for B cells, but B cell depletion in this model is

1240
01:11:15.624 --> 01:11:19.184
complicated because you change the entire lymphoid environment.

1241
01:11:19.223 --> 01:11:22.173
What we wanted to do to sort of avoid some of those things was ask what would

1242
01:11:22.204 --> 01:11:25.284
happen if we co-targeted PD-1 and CD22 together.

1243
01:11:26.044 --> 01:11:29.904
So we built a bispecific antibody where one arm targets CD22,

1244
01:11:30.004 --> 01:11:33.804
one arm targets PD-1, and just ask, this is now sort of primary

1245
01:11:33.884 --> 01:11:37.434
treatment. How does a bispecific targeting PD-1 and

1246
01:11:37.484 --> 01:11:41.464
CD22 compare to single arm molecules targeting CD22

1247
01:11:41.544 --> 01:11:43.144
or PD-1 separately?

1248
01:11:43.964 --> 01:11:47.824
In fact, when we do this, we see a remarkable response of the bispecific in

1249
01:11:47.884 --> 01:11:51.654
reinvigorating the T cells. So numerically, there are way more T cells by frequency

1250
01:11:51.764 --> 01:11:55.464
or number in multiple tissues. We see that these T cells

1251
01:11:55.804 --> 01:11:57.824
are proliferating more. They're also more functional.

1252
01:11:57.904 --> 01:12:01.864
I'm not showing you that data, but we get more interferon, more interferon

1253
01:12:01.904 --> 01:12:05.224
TNF co-production, and we control disease

1254
01:12:05.284 --> 01:12:08.424
substantially better than either of the single R molecules

1255
01:12:08.824 --> 01:12:10.844
that we see here.

1256
01:12:11.744 --> 01:12:15.173
So looks like targeting PD-1 and CD22 is

1257
01:12:15.244 --> 01:12:18.624
beneficial, and it's beneficial by targeting these Tpex populations.

1258
01:12:19.524 --> 01:12:23.204
LCMV is a great model. It's the first place where we saw real responses to

1259
01:12:23.244 --> 01:12:26.384
PD-1 checkpoint blockade in reinvigorating exhausted T cells.

1260
01:12:26.404 --> 01:12:29.724
It's told us a lot about the biology of exhausted T cells, but there are clear

1261
01:12:29.784 --> 01:12:33.144
differences with tumor models. We wanted to ask whether we see the same

1262
01:12:33.184 --> 01:12:37.004
biology, and I'm just going to show you one example of a tumor model in mice.

1263
01:12:38.474 --> 01:12:42.164
This is the AT3 ova model, where we're using a flank version of the

1264
01:12:42.184 --> 01:12:46.044
AT3 tumor model. In the TILS themselves, we put in

1265
01:12:46.084 --> 01:12:48.524
OT1 cells so we could track tumor specific T cells.

1266
01:12:48.564 --> 01:12:49.124
In this case,

1267
01:12:49.984 --> 01:12:53.204
there's a little bit of CD22, but really not much.

1268
01:12:53.704 --> 01:12:56.924
Most of what we see for the tumor specific T cells is actually in the tumor

1269
01:12:56.964 --> 01:13:00.858
draining lymphAnd we think this is important because we think this is where these

1270
01:13:00.908 --> 01:13:04.708
more robust progenitor cells are living, in lymphoid tissue, in the lymphoid

1271
01:13:04.728 --> 01:13:08.088
environments that actually allow them to interact with the proper dendritic cells.

1272
01:13:08.708 --> 01:13:12.688
And so we wanted to ask then, what would happen in this AT3 model

1273
01:13:12.768 --> 01:13:16.628
if we blocked both PD-1 and CD22?

1274
01:13:18.028 --> 01:13:20.988
So we set this up again, AT3 OVA flank model.

1275
01:13:21.168 --> 01:13:24.558
We're not putting in OT1s here. We wanted to sort of make this as difficult as

1276
01:13:24.568 --> 01:13:26.428
possible. And I'll just point out the timing here.

1277
01:13:26.448 --> 01:13:28.428
So we're actually waiting quite late in this model.

1278
01:13:28.468 --> 01:13:32.308
It's very difficult to actually get an effective therapy when we wait this long

1279
01:13:32.348 --> 01:13:35.348
with AT3. In fact, you'll see that our PD-1

1280
01:13:35.808 --> 01:13:38.588
only doesn't have a great effect here.

1281
01:13:39.548 --> 01:13:43.068
But when we block with the bispecific antibody, we see considerable tumor

1282
01:13:43.108 --> 01:13:46.898
control. We also see that we increase the number of T cells in the tumor,

1283
01:13:47.238 --> 01:13:50.728
and especially the number of T cells that look like exhausted T cells infiltrating

1284
01:13:50.748 --> 01:13:53.728
the tumor. We're working on this in a number of other tumor models, and there are a

1285
01:13:53.748 --> 01:13:57.648
bunch more questions that we want to ask here about the role of

1286
01:13:57.688 --> 01:14:01.468
CD22, especially in TLS environments and in the lymphoid

1287
01:14:01.528 --> 01:14:01.848
tissue.

1288
01:14:02.888 --> 01:14:05.368
So let me just summarize quickly and then leave a few minutes for questions.

1289
01:14:06.348 --> 01:14:06.688
So the first

1290
01:14:08.128 --> 01:14:09.808
point I want to make, and summary point,

1291
01:14:10.728 --> 01:14:14.508
is that we've started to think about the molecules we inject

1292
01:14:14.588 --> 01:14:17.158
to induce immunotherapy responses as

1293
01:14:17.208 --> 01:14:20.828
prodrugs. They're not targeting the disease cells themselves.

1294
01:14:21.068 --> 01:14:24.708
And in fact, the mechanism by which we achieve an effect on disease

1295
01:14:25.168 --> 01:14:29.128
is through the changed T cell. So the T cell is really the drug.

1296
01:14:29.548 --> 01:14:33.208
The anti-PD-1 is the prodrug. We think this is important because if we want to

1297
01:14:33.248 --> 01:14:36.888
understand how our drug is working, we need to be studying the

1298
01:14:36.948 --> 01:14:40.928
biology and indeed the pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of that in

1299
01:14:40.968 --> 01:14:41.608
vivo drug.

1300
01:14:42.508 --> 01:14:45.608
Prolonged loss of PD-1 signals is not always an advantage for these cells.

1301
01:14:45.688 --> 01:14:49.348
We see very clearly we're eroding this Tpex biology by

1302
01:14:49.388 --> 01:14:53.048
chronically removing the PD-1 pathway. This makes perfect sense.

1303
01:14:53.148 --> 01:14:56.968
These cells have adapted to reach an equilibrium of

1304
01:14:57.028 --> 01:15:00.288
signaling with the disease, and the T cell.

1305
01:15:00.308 --> 01:15:04.098
And if you change that equilibrium and increase the signal strength, it will have

1306
01:15:04.108 --> 01:15:07.008
an effect on the cells. There's a nice paper from Ron Germain looking early in the

1307
01:15:07.027 --> 01:15:10.448
response suggesting, in fact, PD-1 is used to tune that system.

1308
01:15:11.218 --> 01:15:15.157
A drug holiday allows for sufficient rest for these cells to mount a

1309
01:15:15.268 --> 01:15:18.948
new reinvigoration response. This is, in many ways, T cell

1310
01:15:18.988 --> 01:15:22.948
biology 101. For T cells to remain fit, they need rest from

1311
01:15:23.028 --> 01:15:26.138
stimulation. We've learned this through prime boost vaccines, we've learned this

1312
01:15:26.168 --> 01:15:30.088
through lots of other things. And so by removing PD-1 blockade

1313
01:15:30.128 --> 01:15:33.288
for some period of time and allowing the system to reset, we get another round of

1314
01:15:33.308 --> 01:15:37.248
immune reinvigoration, which gives us additional clinical benefit in

1315
01:15:37.288 --> 01:15:38.008
this mouse model.

1316
01:15:39.628 --> 01:15:43.537
By studying the pharmacodynamic effects of this drug holiday and long-term

1317
01:15:43.648 --> 01:15:46.968
treatment, we were able to reveal other pathways that are useful targets.

1318
01:15:47.388 --> 01:15:51.248
Now, whether CD22 is going to be a blockbuster clinical drug, I don't know.

1319
01:15:51.748 --> 01:15:55.448
But the key point is that by studying that stress

1320
01:15:55.548 --> 01:15:59.157
response, the adaptation that occurs, we can reveal pathways and

1321
01:15:59.208 --> 01:16:03.048
opportunities to change the biology in ways that we can't if we are not

1322
01:16:03.128 --> 01:16:04.988
studying that pharmacodynamic effect.

1323
01:16:05.768 --> 01:16:09.748
And I'll just end by saying that we think it's very important to think about how we

1324
01:16:09.768 --> 01:16:11.588
drug the dynamics of the immune system.

1325
01:16:12.288 --> 01:16:16.168
We published a paper last year or a year and a half ago with Andy Minn, where

1326
01:16:16.208 --> 01:16:20.028
we looked at temporal changes in the way we drug interferon responses

1327
01:16:20.308 --> 01:16:23.788
that are similar to thinking about temporal ways that we can drug the PD-1 pathway

1328
01:16:23.808 --> 01:16:24.688
and TCR signaling.

1329
01:16:26.088 --> 01:16:29.188
So I'm going to end here. I mentioned Xin did almost all of this work.

1330
01:16:29.248 --> 01:16:29.588
We had

1331
01:16:30.388 --> 01:16:33.488
great collaboration with Dave Weiner and Ryan O'Connell helped us with the

1332
01:16:33.548 --> 01:16:36.988
bispecific antibody. I mentioned some of the early work that we did,

1333
01:16:37.708 --> 01:16:40.748
was done by Sean Blackburn, Michael Paley, two previous students in the lab, and

1334
01:16:40.768 --> 01:16:44.188
Alex Hwang, a former fellow in the lab who did a lot of the clinical melanoma work.

1335
01:16:44.808 --> 01:16:46.648
Stop there, and happy to take questions.

1336
01:16:53.248 --> 01:16:56.028
Great talk. Thank you very much. Eben Rosenthal, Vanderbilt.

1337
01:16:56.708 --> 01:17:00.568
So do you think this could be a dose modulation effect?

1338
01:17:00.608 --> 01:17:04.328
In other words, are we giving too high a dose, or is

1339
01:17:04.388 --> 01:17:07.708
the drug holiday maybe affected

1340
01:17:10.348 --> 01:17:12.868
in a more long-term way if we just don't give as much?

1341
01:17:13.228 --> 01:17:16.957
Yeah. It's a great question. Alan Korman was here somewhere and

1342
01:17:17.088 --> 01:17:18.488
may be the better person to answer that.

1343
01:17:19.348 --> 01:17:22.928
In the original studies, only some of which are in the public domain for

1344
01:17:23.148 --> 01:17:23.628
nivo,

1345
01:17:24.608 --> 01:17:28.588
there really wasn't a clear dose cutoff.

1346
01:17:28.888 --> 01:17:32.728
You got pretty effective blockade of the PD-1 pathway, even with about a 5 to

1347
01:17:32.808 --> 01:17:34.648
10 or tenfold lower dose.

1348
01:17:35.448 --> 01:17:38.968
In those early studies, there was a conclusion, I think the data was reasonable,

1349
01:17:39.368 --> 01:17:42.988
that you only need about 60% receptor occupancy for full biological

1350
01:17:43.028 --> 01:17:46.828
effect. So I don't know if we can dose down, especially if the off rate of the

1351
01:17:46.888 --> 01:17:48.368
antibody is so slow.

1352
01:17:49.308 --> 01:17:51.588
It seems to be recycled and seems to be present

1353
01:17:53.388 --> 01:17:55.348
very long term. It's a great question.

1354
01:17:55.548 --> 01:17:59.158
I think it'd be great to have drugs that hit the receptor in different ways.

1355
01:17:59.618 --> 01:18:03.108
My analogy is we're hitting the receptor as just basically an on/off switch.

1356
01:18:03.568 --> 01:18:06.588
There are lots of other pathways that we drug pharmacologically where we use

1357
01:18:06.648 --> 01:18:10.008
nuanced sort of rheostats for those pathways. We don't have them here yet.

1358
01:18:11.948 --> 01:18:12.108
Yeah.

1359
01:18:12.548 --> 01:18:15.708
Amazing talk. So when you have

1360
01:18:16.768 --> 01:18:20.668
the chronic overstimulation of CD8 T cells

1361
01:18:21.408 --> 01:18:24.928
with anti-PD-1, you have overstimulation and probably some

1362
01:18:24.968 --> 01:18:28.788
apoptosis in CD8 T cells, and that's maybe why you don't

1363
01:18:28.868 --> 01:18:32.508
see the intermediate exhausted. Then you have upregulation of

1364
01:18:32.548 --> 01:18:36.528
CD22. If you block CD22, then you will have

1365
01:18:36.568 --> 01:18:39.928
even more stimulation because that's a repressor, right?

1366
01:18:40.508 --> 01:18:41.908
So how come that works?

1367
01:18:42.068 --> 01:18:45.398
Yes. Yeah, great question. I'm so glad you asked this because it is a really

1368
01:18:45.408 --> 01:18:49.268
important point. So most of these kind of things will be very

1369
01:18:49.308 --> 01:18:51.788
useful, but temporarily, right? And so

1370
01:18:51.828 --> 01:18:55.768
we've only done one thing that seems to change the epigenetics

1371
01:18:55.788 --> 01:18:58.638
of exhausted T cells, and it has to do with STAT5 activation.

1372
01:18:59.148 --> 01:19:03.048
I don't think these drugs are really changing the epigenetics of who these cells

1373
01:19:03.148 --> 01:19:07.108
are. So what we're trying to do is sort of get waves of new cells coming out.

1374
01:19:07.248 --> 01:19:08.628
You're right, they will be short-term.

1375
01:19:09.048 --> 01:19:12.972
And if we ask for thatThat bolus of cells to be

1376
01:19:13.032 --> 01:19:14.632
continually propagated, we're going to lose.

1377
01:19:15.172 --> 01:19:18.952
But if we can drug the dynamics so we can get waves of new cells, we should be able

1378
01:19:18.972 --> 01:19:22.212
to do this over and over again. You're right, the cells we get will be short-term,

1379
01:19:22.372 --> 01:19:25.932
and we think that these CD22 provoked cells will also be

1380
01:19:25.992 --> 01:19:28.852
short-term and will die off. If we could keep them alive longer, we would.

1381
01:19:28.892 --> 01:19:32.592
And actually, the STAT5 drugging seems to keep them alive longer, not with

1382
01:19:32.632 --> 01:19:36.012
CD22, but with PD-1. So it's a great question. I think you're exactly right.

1383
01:19:37.732 --> 01:19:38.172
Yeah, Eric?

1384
01:19:38.432 --> 01:19:42.132
Great talk, John. Two questions. The first one, do you see this

1385
01:19:42.152 --> 01:19:43.712
population of CD22

1386
01:19:44.912 --> 01:19:47.972
in humans? First question, obvious question, sorry about that.

1387
01:19:48.012 --> 01:19:48.632
The second one,

1388
01:19:49.632 --> 01:19:53.092
do you know whether there are some ligands of CD22 which are very

1389
01:19:53.112 --> 01:19:55.132
important for what you are describing?

1390
01:19:55.272 --> 01:19:58.802
Yeah, both great questions. So we've been looking in humans, and it's a reason why

1391
01:19:58.832 --> 01:20:02.432
I made the point about the tumor-draining lymph node versus the tumor.

1392
01:20:02.452 --> 01:20:06.422
When we look in tumor, we can see them, but it's like the tumor in mouse,

1393
01:20:06.692 --> 01:20:08.972
very, very few CD22 positive cells.

1394
01:20:08.992 --> 01:20:12.412
But these are tumors that don't have very much TLS structure, head, neck, and

1395
01:20:12.452 --> 01:20:12.952
melanoma.

1396
01:20:14.252 --> 01:20:17.972
We are trying to get our hands on tumor-draining lymph nodes to see if we can see

1397
01:20:18.032 --> 01:20:20.052
more there. When we look in the public

1398
01:20:20.852 --> 01:20:23.532
RNAseq databases, we can see them, but they're pretty rare.

1399
01:20:23.672 --> 01:20:26.972
So jury's still out on how abundant they will be in humans.

1400
01:20:27.032 --> 01:20:29.732
But I'd love to get tumor-draining lymph nodes to look at this more if we could.

1401
01:20:30.372 --> 01:20:32.672
In terms of ligand, CD22 is a ligand of itself.

1402
01:20:33.372 --> 01:20:37.332
It's also buying sialic acids on typically APCs

1403
01:20:37.572 --> 01:20:40.992
for the germinal center B cells. Probably large molecules like

1404
01:20:41.052 --> 01:20:43.632
CD43, CD45 with their sialic acids.

1405
01:20:43.952 --> 01:20:46.132
We haven't looked at that very carefully yet, but that's the next question.

1406
01:20:47.232 --> 01:20:47.612
Yeah, Eric.

1407
01:20:47.772 --> 01:20:48.452
Beautiful story.

1408
01:20:49.892 --> 01:20:53.872
When you were doing your two monoclonals independently, so PD-1 and then

1409
01:20:53.932 --> 01:20:54.552
CD22,

1410
01:20:55.672 --> 01:20:59.432
would you say that was more of a model of adaptive resistance?

1411
01:21:00.612 --> 01:21:02.972
Yeah, we think about this as adaptive resistance.

1412
01:21:03.052 --> 01:21:05.912
When you're blocking PD-1 long-term,

1413
01:21:07.992 --> 01:21:11.932
the populations of cells have adapted to a new proliferative

1414
01:21:11.972 --> 01:21:15.052
hierarchy that is no longer responsive to PD-1 blockade.

1415
01:21:16.312 --> 01:21:19.952
That is a form of adaptive resistance that's sort of T cell intrinsic, and we can

1416
01:21:19.992 --> 01:21:21.652
overcome that with CD22 blockade.

1417
01:21:21.712 --> 01:21:22.212
Okay, thanks.

1418
01:21:22.512 --> 01:21:23.112
Yeah. Thanks.

1419
01:21:24.152 --> 01:21:24.292
Yeah.

1420
01:21:25.392 --> 01:21:29.052
Hi. Great talk. I have a question. So when

1421
01:21:29.172 --> 01:21:31.312
you say there is a drug holiday,

1422
01:21:32.752 --> 01:21:36.632
so what if the cancer is more aggressive and the T cells are

1423
01:21:36.672 --> 01:21:40.132
getting a lot of antigenic stimulation and the TPECs

1424
01:21:40.792 --> 01:21:44.222
have already become TX? So how does the

1425
01:21:44.412 --> 01:21:48.332
second dose of the drug work in that situation?

1426
01:21:48.832 --> 01:21:50.552
Yeah. So there are two questions embedded there.

1427
01:21:50.652 --> 01:21:54.532
One is, of course, if tumors are progressing, you may not want to stop therapy.

1428
01:21:54.572 --> 01:21:57.972
It's a very difficult kind of ethical question and clinical question.

1429
01:21:58.712 --> 01:22:00.972
I recognize that, and we don't have a good answer for that yet.

1430
01:22:01.532 --> 01:22:05.401
When you have high antigen burden, in most cases, there are always

1431
01:22:05.452 --> 01:22:09.392
these TPEC cells there. You can think about this developmental biology

1432
01:22:09.432 --> 01:22:12.482
exactly the same as any other tissue, including the hematopoietic system.

1433
01:22:13.212 --> 01:22:14.992
Even when you have lymphopenia,

1434
01:22:16.112 --> 01:22:18.952
your HSCs are still making more cells.

1435
01:22:19.012 --> 01:22:22.241
Just because there's been stress on the system, it doesn't mean that the HSCs, or

1436
01:22:22.272 --> 01:22:24.172
in this case, the TPECs, go away entirely.

1437
01:22:24.732 --> 01:22:28.692
What often happens when you stress that system is you take away the more activated

1438
01:22:28.892 --> 01:22:31.432
stem cells and you preserve the more quiescent stem cells.

1439
01:22:31.582 --> 01:22:34.892
